metadata.description:
THE NEW BABYLONIANS ARE THE PEOPLE OF NEW BABYLON

We are a creative global community of metaverse nomads, to travel with us you will need a passport, the first GENERATIVE AND INTERACTIVE PFP CITIZENSHIP NFT PROJECT

For this you will need to collect a landscape, a New Babylonian, and the best assets to create your New Babylonian PFP CITIZENSHIP.
 
Fill your bag with the best assets and join us in this journey

New Babylon Landscapes is a rare first-generation generative resource from the New Babylonians collection, there are 14,691,978 possible editions of Undiscovered Landscapes, but only 200 can be minted.  

This first generation New Babylon Landscapes can be integrated with other assets in this collection and exchanged for a unique PFP to be minted in the New Babylon collection on OBJKT.com.

This unique PFP will be created in a generative and relational way, where you, the collector, are the co-artist of the project and who create the final combination and story that will describe the journey of your New Babylonian.

To merge all your assets into one New Babylonian and and create his story join our discord:

https://discord.com/invite/gSWQJCJ52v 

or contact us via Twitter

https://twitter.com/NewBabylonian 

There will be 4 generations of New Babylonians, totaling 1000 New Babylonians. The first generation contains 100 New Babylonians, but their assets range from 70-200 editions, which may or may not all be used in the first generation.

Each of the Assets after merged into a single New Babylonians will be burned, which will make all items from the first generation rare, as the ones left can be used in the next 4 generations of New Babylonians, and each generation the editions of this NFT will be scarcer, until all editions are burned.

join our journey and get yours NEW BABYLONIAN PFP CITIZENSHIP

 more information on our websitet

https://www.newbabylon.xyz/

metadata.name: Tesseract #442
metadata.description:
'Tesseract' is a generative collection drawing on the concept of the cube from oneirology, the interpretation of dreams. In many mythologies and fields of study, the square is considered a 'perfect shape', thus with its abstraction into three isometric dimensions, the cube is seen by some as a representation of the various aspects of the human condition.

In 'Tesseract', the ribbons flowing between the cubes represent the shared experiences that connect us all. No matter how different our lives might be, we all go through the same joys, sorrows, trials, tribulations and experience attachments of varying degrees. 

It is these experiences that bind us together and make us who we are. With these concepts in mind, viewers are invited to interpret each composition as it relates to them and their unique story, from the perspective of that which has been and that which is yet to be experienced.

Press 'S' to save a high resolution PNG at 2400 x 3396 px.

metadata.name: Sketches:Pairs of Tails:Majestic Creatures #29
metadata.description:
Addendum to Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

There is a significantly common phenomena in which Pairs of "Tails of Majestic Creatures" are found together. Various sketches of these "Pairs" have been collated and are available, free of charge, the collectors of the initial Tails of Majestic Creatures collection based upon a recently taken collection registry snapshot. 

These sketches are available on a one per collector basis and for a limited time only after which they will no longer be accessible.

The sketches come in 2 forms - an ink and color style, and a pencil style - for which different colored paper has been used.

The digitally minded can press s to get a 5000x3000 download of a sketch.

metadata.name: Machine Spirit #12
metadata.description:
Machine Spirit picks up where Equilibrium and Equanimity left off. Notwithstanding my love for generative mountains, trees, and (especially) cities, my personal artistic quest remains to produce an algorithm that generates convincing abstract art in the style of Richter and Rothko. The project you are looking at is my best attempt yet.

Trigger warning: some iterations produce rapidly flashing colors which may pose a risk of seizure to people with photosensitive epilepsy or similar conditions.

While the final result is a static image, the live view visualizes how the image is generated. It goes something like this: you start with a grid of cells in random colors, and you feed that into a carefully customized cellular automaton, where the color of each cell is determined by the color of that cell and its neighbours in the previous generation. If you end up with a single color over-powering all the others, or too many different fragmented colors, you start over. But when you reach a stable state with two or three colors, you have achieved your goal: a mathematical balance in color and composition that tends to be aesthetically pleasing as well. You then select a suitable canvas color and run a more computationally intensive rendering process, which makes the end result look more like physical paint on canvas, while retaining the subtle traces of its digital origins.

Press [b]leed, [c]anvas or [d]ensity in the live view to cycle through variations, or [p]rint to save a high resolution capture.

All iterations eventually converge to a stable state, but in theory this could last arbitrarily long, and on rare occasions it may take longer than 5 minutes, in which case the captured preview will be different from the final result. This artwork is fully generative and was hand-coded in 7,500 characters of plain JavaScript code. I didn't use any libraries, but I did take inspiration from an essay by Tyler Hobbs on polygon deformation techniques.

Forever limited to 250 editions on the Tezos blockchain. I truly hope you will enjoy yours. London, March 2022.

metadata.name: Machine 12: slates #45
metadata.description:
Machine 12 generates a series of steel slates that reflect a bright neon/vintage mix of colors. 
The composition refers to an 80s aesthetic and consists of 1, 2 or 3 slates, oriented horizontally or vertically. 

Features include: 
- 9 distinct color palettes  
- 1,2 or 3 slates
- horizontal or vertical orientation
- an additional frame on top of the slates
- the presence of additional spheres
- a shadow

metadata.name: Off the grid V.2 #32
metadata.description:
Vanilla JS + SVG
January 2022

Edition of 512

"Off the grid" is my attempt to bring human imperfection to the strict formality of a generative grid-based piece.

Grid-plotted geometric forms are very slightly offset, rotated out of position by a degree or two, or absented entirely from the grid. The number of passes is dictated by the hash, and the results will vary from minimal (4 passes) to maximal (13 passes). The sizes of the forms can vary or be all the same, leading to quite different outputs, further emphasized by the different 'canvas' sizes.

The features are:
Format (Portrait, Landscape or Square), Palette (10 in total), Coverage (Full or Indented), Passes (the number of times the algorithm makes a grid) and Sizes (the sizes of the shapes in the grid, Single [one size] or Multiple).

'S' saves an SVG
'P' saves a PNG

[Please note this project will display, but will not work as intended on most IOS devices]
